Adding a command-line option to FM3.

1. 
Read and edit compiler/lib/FM3HelpText.  Please follow the general
conventions it describes.  Document your option in the same way as
those already there.  Think up a long form option spelling, using only
lowercase letters and imbedded hyphens.  Note whether it is boolean,
if it accumulates, and its default value.

2.
Edit metaprogs/gentok/gen/FM3CLToks.gentok.  Think up a Modula3
identifier, beginning with "Clt", for an integer constant that will
denote your new option inside the compiler.  Add a line with it
and the command-line option spelling, like those already there.  Add
any appropriate comments in Modula3 comment syntax.  Be careful not
to duplicate a short or long option already there. 

Some time before you recompile the compiler, you will need to run the
gentok command found in a comment near the top of FM3CLToks.gentok, in
directory metaprogs/gentok/gen.  This will generate some files named
FM3CLToks* used by the compiler.  Required symlinks to these are
already in place.

3.
Edit file compiler/src/FM3CLOptions.i3.  This contains global variabls
where the parsed and decoded values of command-line options are
stored, for access by code that carries them out.  Add any needed
variable(s) for your new option.  If it's a boolean option, nothing
needs to be declared here.  Otherwise, if it has a single argument,
see BuildDir for inspiration. If it accumulates values from multiple
instances of the option, see ResourceDirNameList for inspiration.

4.
Edit file compiler/src/FM3CLArgs.m3.  This parses the options and
stores results in FM3CLOptions.i3.  Add a line in SetDefaults for the
default value of you option.  If your option has a short form, add 
a case to PaHyphenArg.  Add a case to PaTwoHypenArg for your long
form.  CltStdErr is an example of a plain boolean option.  CltBuildDir
is an example of a non-boolean, non-accumulating option.  CltImportDir
is an example of an accumulating option.

Note that some options need to set more than one variable.  Finally,
add cases for any interactions among different options to
ComputeDerivedInfo.  This is called after all options have been
parsed, so no problems with option order on the command line.

5.
Finally add code wherever needed to carry out what your option
requires.  You can access the variables in FM3CLOptions directly, or
push their values out to another interface at startup time.